title: bandana_waddle_dee
body:
A strong individual [[Waddle Dee]] distinguished by his blue [[bandana]]. He is often seen with [[King Dedede]], acting as a sidekick.

Initially a minor enemy, he has seen a spike in popularity since his role in [i][[Kirby Super Star Ultra]][/i] and especially his playable appearance in [i][[Kirby's Return to Dream Land]][/i]. Since then, his character has been fleshed out to be not only fiercely loyal to Dedede, but also a close friend to [[Kirby]] who is willing to help out in even the toughest of battles.

title: ninamori_eri
body: Ninamori Eri ([[FLCL]]) is the daughter of the mayor of Mabase and the president of [[nandaba_naota|Naota's]] sixth grade class. Ninamori is a complex character like Naota she is obsessed with acting grown-up, but she often loses her composure when angry or excited. Ninamori hides her frustration with her father's sex scandal, and rigs an election for the school play so that she gets the lead role while Naota gets cast opposite her, hinting that she has a crush on him.

title: lion_tamer
body:
The original version of [[Chris Jericho]]'s [[Walls of Jericho]] signature move. 

Truly the more painful and more brutal version of the Walls of Jericho, this is also a higher-angle [[boston crab]] but with the addition of the wrestler using a single knee to add additional pressure by pressing it into the opponent's back or on the back of the opponent's neck.
Chris Jericho rarely uses the Liontamer anymore because it is very difficult to perform on larger opponents and the legit danger this move may cause if applied incorrectly.

[[WWE]] NXT wrestler Roderick Strong also uses this [[submission hold]] which he calls the [i]Strong Hold[/i]. This version focuses more on the lower back of the opponent, which fits to his "Messiah of the Backbreaker" nickname.

title: isabella_valentine
body:
An anti-heroine character from [[Namco]]'s [[Soulcalibur]] series of fighting games, also known as Ivy for short. 

A reclusive English noblewoman and alchemist, Ivy suffers from a blood curse that ties her to the corruptive weapon [[Soul Edge (weapon)|Soul Edge]], and she intends to find a way to break that curse. Visually, she is famed for her [[short hair|short]], [[white hair|white]]/[[silver hair|silver]] hair, her [[large breasts]], and her revealing leather outfit she wears into battle that varies with each game. Her weapon of choice is a [[whip sword]] of her own design that can freely expand and contract between a regular sword and the extended whip-sword form, a weapon that moves according to her will. She is known to show dominant, almost sadist, tendencies while fighting, including stepping on her enemies on the ground and turning them into a [[human chair|chair]] as part of one of her throws.

Ivy's biological father is the dread pirate [[Cervantes de Leon]] and the reason for her blood curse.

title: gustav_munchausen
body:
Gustav Munchausen (Occasionally, and erroneously, spelled 'Gustab'), is a character from [[The King of Fighters]].

Gustav was introduced in the GBA spinoff game [[the_king_of_fighters_ex2|The King of Fighters EX2: Neo Blood]], where he hosted said game's tournament. Lusting for supernatural powers, despite being a multimillionaire already, Gustav channels the spirit of [[Goenitz]] into Sinobu Amou, the game's boss character, for use as his puppet. After Sinobu is defeated by the player, Gustav disappears without any explanation.

Gustav is much more infamously known due to his inclusion as the final boss of the [[M.U.G.E.N]]-developed King of Fighters fangame [i]The King of Fighters Memorial[/i]. Story-wise, Gustav hosts another King of Fighters tournament to get revenge on [[kusanagi_kyou|Kyo Kusanagi]] and [[yagami_iori|Iori Yagami]] for foiling his plans in EX2, requesting the help of his close assistant [[Psyqhical]]. With his monetary powers, Gustav manages to create clones of many major boss characters from the King of Fighters series, including [[Rugal Bernstein]], [[Krizalid]], [[zero_(kof)|both versions]] [[Original Zero|of Zero]], [[igniz_(kof)|Igniz]], and even Kyo and Iori themselves.

Gustav's appearance in [I]Memorial[/i] is heavily based off of [[oswald_(kof)|Oswald]]'s sprite sheet, therefore giving him very overdramatic poses. In-game, he is absurdly overpowered; being able to make use of infinite priority normals and projectiles, and full screen special attacks.

[[Hei Meiling]] is an edit of him.

title: muff
body:
A muff is a fashion accessory for outdoors usually made of a cylinder of fur or fabric with both ends open for keeping the hands warm. It was introduced to women's fashion in the 16th century and was popular with both men and women in the 17th and 18th centuries. By the early 20th century, muffs were used in England only by women. It is also reported that the fashion largely fell out of style in the 19th century.

It briefly returned in the late 1940s and 1950s, and was also developed as a motorcycle accessory for attachment as rider-protection and comfort during the cooler months.

title: morisato_keiichi
body:
Morisato Keiichi (森里 螢一 Morisato Keiichi) is the protagonist of the "[[Aa Megami-sama|Ah! My goddess]]" series. He starts out as a student of the Nekomi Institute of Technology and a member of the NIT Motor Club, who actually used to live in an all male dorm, along with his senpai and a few more members of his Club. 

One day, as he tries to order takeout, Keiichi accidentally dials the Goddess Relief Office, which causes [[belldandy|Belldandy]] to arrive on Earth. She quickly explains to him that he was chosen by Heavens to be granted a single wish, but Keiichi thinks that the whole thing is an elaborate farce set up by his senpai, and comes up with a joke instead. He more or less wishes her to stay with him forever, and immediately comments about that being a crazy wish, although... Belldandy probably thought otherwise and actually submits this request to Heavens. Being kicked out from the dorm for bringing in a girl (as his friends have no idea of Belldandy's true nature as a goddess), Keiichi finds himself on the streets along with Belldandy, and soon searches for a place for them to stay. From that point on, Belldandy's sisters, as well as a couple more goddesses and even demons show up in his life, and (willingly or not) help him to deepen his bond with Belldandy that eventually nurtures into a proper relationship. 

Voiced by: "Masami Kikuchi":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masami_Kikuchi]

title: kokoro_(vocaloid)
body:
ココロ (Heart)
A song for [[Kagamine Rin]]. By Toraboruta-P (トラボルタP) w/ illustrations and PV by Fukusanbutsu-P (副産物Ｐ).

The song tells a story about a robot (Rin) made by a lonely scientist, but is missing a program unable to be made: a Heart. Some time after her creation, her scientist passes away, leaving her alone for several hundred years. She begins to wonder about her creation and makes a wish. She accesses the files that her creator had left and finally gains a Heart. In the process, she discovers what it's like to be happy and sad. With her new feelings, she gratefully dedicates all of the songs that she sings to her creator. In the end, the miracle robot had a short in her system and could no longer sing. However, she had a smile on her face in her last moments, resembling an angel. - Wiki

* "NicoNico video":http://www.nicovideo.jp/watch/sm2500648
* "YouTube video":http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DxvVR63KAcM

h6. Kokoro/Kiseki (Heart/Miracle) by Jun-P

A popular variation on the song, featuring [[Kagamine Len]] in the role of the professor. It tells the story of how he built her and came to make her future "heart", but he dies long before he can get to see her use it. The true answer song by Torabuta-P, "Sayonara, Arigatou", more or less follows the same plot, but has [[Kamui Gakupo]] in the role of the professor instead.

title: trans-am
body:
In the series [[Gundam 00]], it is an inherent feature of the [[GN Drive]] (Tau) that temporarily increases their GN Particle output beyond normal parameters for greatly enhanced combat performance. This is a double-edged sword, because this ability only lasts for a limited time and severely lowers the Mobile Suit's performance afterward -- or worse, destroys the GN Drive Tau equipped on the MS.

It also gives the GN Drive-equipped unit a pink-reddish hue when used, a homage to the urban legend (even in-universe in the UC timeline) that any red mobile suit that [[Char Aznable]] pilots goes three times faster.

title: sailor_senshi_uniform
body:
The iconic costume worn by the [[Sailor Senshi]] in [[Bishoujo Senshi Sailor Moon]]. Its basic design is comprised of the following, starting from the top:

* [[circlet]]
* [[earrings]]
* [[choker]]
* [[sailor collar]]
* a [[bow]] and [[brooch]] on the chest
* [[white gloves|white]] [[elbow gloves]] (hand gloves for Sailors Uranus and Neptune)
* [[white leotard]] with a [[pleated skirt]] over the waist
* a [[back bow|bow on the back of the waist]]
* any variety of footwear

Each of the Sailor Senshi wear different theme colors and have design variations of the above, but the overall uniform is generally the same.

Due to them wearing skirts, it's not immediately obvious that they are wearing leotards. Because of this, images where the leotard can be seen from under the skirt usually get tagged as [[white panties]] due to Danbooru's policy of "tag what you see".

Note that this uniform represents Earth's Sailor Senshi, while warriors from different star systems like the Sailor Starlights and Shadow Galactica have completely different designs, with the sailor collar being the only consistent design aspect.

h4.See also

* [[List of Uniforms]]

Her journey becomes harder and harder on herself, which has the sardonic [[Ryudo (Grandia)|Ryudo]] grow concerned for her welfare.
